Rate Limiting Decorator with Redis
Posted by Armin Ronacher on 2011-09-09 @ 23:43 and filed in Decorators

Sometimes you want to rate limit a view (for example an API). This is very simple to do with redis and a simple decorator. The idea is that we limit a view for a certain period of time and increment a counter in redis. The key for this counter shall be the current IP (or userid) plus the current endpoint plus the time when the rate limit resets.

```class submitPilih(Form):
    sf = SelectField("Test", coerce=int)

@app.route('/haha', methods=['GET', 'POST'])
def haha():
    form = submitPilih()    
    form.sf.choices = [(0, "test0"), (1, "test1")]
    form.sf.default = 0
    form.process()

    return render_template("haha.html",
        form=form)```

Welcome to the AMP Roadshow Jakarta!
The roadshow is a free, single day event supported and organized by members of the AMP team. You're looking at the registration page for the Jakarta event ‚Äì for more general information about the roadshow, head to the AMP Roadshow site.

What's AMP?
The AMP Project, short for Accelerated Mobile Pages, is an open-source initiative aiming to make the web better for all. The project enables the creation of websites and ads that are consistently fast, beautiful and high-performing across devices and distribution platforms.

Why should I come?
Whether you're a developer starting to become interested in AMP, or whether you want to build even more advanced, interactive AMP pages, or even if you're a CTO setting your companies' strategy, you should come.

Please join us to learn about building, monetizing and deploying highly interactive, responsive sites with AMP. And bring your laptop!

Register AMP Roadshow Jakarta here: https://events.withgoogle.com/amp-roadshow-jakarta/

Join another roadshow in near your city? Check this out: https://www.ampproject.org/amp-roadshow/

Creating a minimal yet structured REST API app with Flask-Journey

Hello!

 

I've recently released an extension called Flask-Journey that targets three, perhaps trivial, but yet important areas when building a REST API:

* blueprint/route management
* validation
* (de)serialization

 

Flask-journey focuses on making the process of validation and (de)serialization of data to/from python objects according to marshmallow and/or marshmallow_sqlalchemy schemas, simple and elegant, by providing these features in a drop-in replacement for the **Blueprint.route** decorator.

 

When it comes to blueprints, the **Journey** API helps segregate, group and have them registered with ease while providing methods for listing their routes, either in simple or detailed JSON form.

 

I've created a full working example showing how to utilize the extension in a small (without extras) yet well-structured "starter" REST API app:

https://github.com/rbw0/flask-journey/tree/master/examples/full

 

Let me know if you have any questions, or just create a PR or issue on GH If you have improvements or found a bug.

Selamat pagi. Maaf menganggu, mau nanya diantara temen2 ada yang bisa bantuin gak ngasih/nemuin solusi buat ngeeksekusi beberapa (20) fungsi flask dengan method Get/Post/Delete pada file Csv.
#Misalnya : Nambah line baru pada file CSVnya, Ngehapus data di line tengah pada file CSV dll

Nama file Csv : data3.csv
Kolomnya : data dan sign

Nah disini aku udh mempelajari sedikit2 tentang python dan flask tapi masih kurang paham karena masih sangat awam. 

Salah satu contoh code yang aku pelajarin terkait python ini sih " nambah line baru pada file CSV " tapi masih ada saja yang salah. Aku mau nunjukin codenya tapi klau masih sangat kurang mohon di mengerti yah hehe
#codenya seperti ini :

def save_data(data):
    filename = "data3.csv"
    header="sata,sign"+""
    #Check whether the file exists
    if(os.path.exists(os.path.expanduser(filename))==False):
        file = open(os.path.expanduser(filename),"wb")
        file.write(bytes(header, encoding="ascii",errors="ignore"))
        file.close()

    file = open(os.path.expanduser(filename),"a")
    i=0
    while (i < len(data)):
        if((i+1)==len(data)
           file.write(data[i]+"")
        else:
            file.write(data[i]+";")
        i+=1
    file.close()
